        <script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>

        <style type="text/css">

#main .nav-pills {
margin-top: 20px;
margin-bottom: 10px;
}
#main .nav-pills > li > a {
background-color: #EEEEEE;
background-image: none;
background-position: 0 0;
}
#main .nav-pills > li > a:hover {
color: #FFFFFF !important;
background-color: #9F2042;
}
#main .nav-pills > li.active > a,
#main .nav-pills > li.active > a:hover,
#main .nav-pills > li.active > a:focus {
color: #FFFFFF !important;
background-color: #9F2042;
}

.chisq-results {
margin: -20px 0px 35px 20px;
font-size: 90%;
font-style: italic;
}

img.image-thumb {
width: 250px;
border: 1px solid #CCC;
padding: 2px;
}
img.image-lb {
cursor: pointer;
}
.figure {
margin: 5px 10px 30px 0px;
display: table;
text-align: center;
}
.figure img {
margin-bottom: 5px;
}
.figure p.caption {
font-style: italic;
font-size: 90%;
}

.datatables {
margin: 2em 0em;
}
.dataTables_length,
.dataTables_filter,
.dataTables_info,
.dataTables_paginate {
font-size: 90%;
}
.pagedtable-index-current {
font-weight: bold;
}
#main a.anchor-section {
color: #BBB;

        <script>$( document ).ready(function() {

    // Fix for dots in level 1 and level 2 titles
    $('body .section.level1').each(function () {
      $(this).attr("id", $(this).attr("id").replace(/\./g, "-"));
    });
    $('body .section.level2').each(function () {
      $(this).attr("id", $(this).attr("id").replace(/\./g, "-"));
    });
    $('#toc ul li a').each(function () {
      $(this).attr("href", $(this).attr("href").replace(/\./g, "-"));
    });

    // Shift nav in mobile when clicking the menu.
    $(document).on('click', "[data-toggle='wy-nav-top']", function() {
      $("[data-toggle='wy-nav-shift']").toggleClass("shift");
    });
    // Close menu when you click a link.
    $(document).on('click', "#toc ul li a", function() {
      $("[data-toggle='wy-nav-shift']").removeClass("shift");
    });
    // Close menu when you click on main content
    $(document).on('click', "#main, #header", function() {
      $("[data-toggle='wy-nav-shift']").removeClass("shift");
    });

    // Make tables responsive
    $("#main table").wrap("<div class='table-wrapper'></div>");

    // ScrollSpy also requires that we use a Bootstrap nav component.
    $('#toc ul').first().addClass('nav');
    $('body').scrollspy({target: '#toc'});

    // add sticky table headers
    //$('table').stickyTableHeaders();

});
</script>

<div id="main">
<div id="i-project-introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>I: Project Introduction</h1>
<p><em>You can navigate this document by clicking on headings and
subheadings in the table of contents on the left</em>.</p>
<p><em>Throughout this document, the kable function is used to cleanly
display data</em>.</p>
<p>This dataset contains the key performance metrics of NBA players in
their rookie (first) season in the NBA League and additional information
about how they entered the league.</p>
<p>The objective of this project is to build classification models to
predict whether or not players will play at least 5 years in the NBA,
given how they performed in their rookie season. We would like to better
understand what factors make players more likely to thrive in the NBA.
Given the term structure of rookie contracts, players who make it to
year 5 have a higher chance of getting another contract and playing
several more years.</p>
<p>This dataset was collected from <a href="https://data.world/exercises/logistic-regression-exercise-1" class="uri">https://data.world/exercises/logistic-regression-exercise-1</a>.</p>
<p>Additional data regarding the year players were drafted, the round
they were drafted in, the year they debuted, the team they played for
and that teams record at the end of the season was web scraped from
Wikipedia using a Python script we wrote.</p>
<div id="variable-descriptions" class="section level2">
<h2>Variable descriptions</h2>
<div id="outcome" class="section level3">
<h3>Outcome</h3>
<p><strong>TARGET_5Yrs</strong>: Dummy variable with value 1 for players
who went on to play 5 or more years in the league, and 0 for those that
did not.</p>
</div>
<div id="predictors" class="section level3">
<h3>Predictors</h3>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><strong>GP</strong> - Games played [integer]</li>
<li><strong>MIN</strong> - Average minutes played per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>PTS</strong> - Average points per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FGM</strong> - Average field goals made per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FGA</strong> - Average field goal attempts [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FG%</strong> - Average field goal success percentage
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>3P Made</strong> - Average three-pointers made per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>3PA</strong> - Average three-pointers attempted per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>3P%</strong> - Average three-pointer success percentage per
game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FTM</strong> - Average free throws made per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FTA</strong> - Average free throws attempted per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>FT%</strong> - Average free throw success percentage
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>OREB</strong> - Average offensive rebounds per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>DREB</strong> - Average defensive rebounds per game
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>REB</strong> - Average rebounds per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>AST</strong> - Average assists per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>STL</strong> - Average steals per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>BLK</strong> - Average blocks per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>TOV</strong> - Average turnovers per game [numeric]</li>
<li><strong>Year_Drafted</strong> - Year the player declared for the
draft [integer]</li>
<li><strong>Round_Drafted</strong> - Round of draft [character -
contains U for undrafted]</li>
<li><strong>Team</strong> - Team played for [character]</li>
<li><strong>Win_Percentage</strong> - Teams win percentage
[numeric]</li>
<li><strong>Position</strong> - Position played in [character]</li>
<li><strong>Year_Debut</strong> - Year of debut [integer]</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>

<div id="ii-exploratory-data-analysis-eda-of-raw-data" class="section level1">
<h1>II: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) of raw data</h1>
<div id="summary-statistics" class="section level2">
<h2>Summary statistics</h2>
<p>Using the powerful summary function, we can check each column for
missing, negative (where there shouldnt be), infinite and anomalous
values. We can also make sure all values fall within obvious expected
ranges for particular variables (year drafted, win percentage etc.),
using the minimum and maximum statistics.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb4"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1"><a href="#cb4-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">summary</span>(raw_data)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##      Name                 GP             MIN             PTS

<p><strong>Insights:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Values for year drafted and year debut are all in the expected
range (between 1971 and 2016).</p></li>
<li><p>Values for win percentage are all between 0 and 100, as
expected.</p></li>
<li><p>The character variables (name, round drafted, team and position)
all have the expected number of observations (1299).</p></li>
<li><p>Using the TARGET_5Yrs variable, we see that 817 (63%) of players
in the sample reached 5 years, and 482 (37%) did not.</p></li>
<li><p>A small number of NAs are present in the expected 3 pointers
column (10 observations). Given this is less than 1% of the sample size,
we make the decision to drop all observations with a missing value for
any variable, as it will make the model-fitting easier while costing
very little in accuracy.</p></li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_no_nas <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">na.omit</span>(raw_data)</span>
<span id="cb6-2"><a href="#cb6-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">sprintf</span>(<span class="st">&quot;NAs omitted, number of obs falls from %s to %s&quot;</span>, <span class="fu">nrow</span>(raw_data), <span class="fu">nrow</span>(data_no_nas))</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;NAs omitted, number of obs falls from 1299 to 1289&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="remove-collinear-and-irrelevant-variables" class="section level2">
<h2>Remove collinear and irrelevant variables</h2>
<p>For some aspects of game performance, such as free throws, we have 3
variables. One for attempts, one for successes, and one for percentage
success = 100*(attempts/successes). Including all three variables leads
to collinearity when we come to build models, as each can be calculated
directly from the other two. So, we drop the attempts variables to avoid
multicollinearity issues.</p>
<p>Also, total rebounds = offensive rebounds + defensive rebounds, so we
drop the total rebounds variable.</p>
<p>We also drop the following variables:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p><strong>Player names</strong>, as they will serve no purpose in
our analysis.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Team names</strong>, as most of the predictive power of
the team should be captured by the team win percentage variable (which
is far easier to work with than 30 dummy variables for the
teams).</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Year drafted</strong>, as this information is captured
more effectively by the year debut variable. Additionally, there are
instances where players declare for the draft, but do not make their
debut in the same year for various reasons. For example, NBA Hall of
Famer David Robinson was selected 1st overall in the NBA Draft by the
San Antonio Spurs but could not play for two years because he had to
fulfil his active-duty obligations with the Navy.</p></li>
</ol>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb8"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1"><a href="#cb8-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_no_nas <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb8-2"><a href="#cb8-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="sc">-</span>Name, <span class="sc">-</span>Year_Drafted, <span class="sc">-</span>Team, <span class="sc">-</span>FGA, <span class="sc">-</span>X3PA, <span class="sc">-</span>FTA, <span class="sc">-</span>REB)</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="check-character-variable-values" class="section level2">
<h2>Check character variable values</h2>
<p>The summary function does a good job of making sure the numeric
values all fall within the expected ranges. However, non-numeric
variables can also contain errors. We check for this by getting the
distinct values for the two remaining columns with character type (Round
Drafted and Position).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb9"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb9-1"><a href="#cb9-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">count</span>(Round_Drafted) <span class="co">#%&gt;% arrange(Round_Drafted)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##    Round_Drafted   n
## 1              1 712
## 2             10   1
## 3              2 338
## 4              3  38
## 5              4  24
## 6              5   4
## 7              6   7
## 8              7   5
## 9              8   3
## 10             U 137
## 11            U   20</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb11"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb11-1"><a href="#cb11-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">count</span>(Position)<span class="co"># %&gt;% arrange(Position)</span></span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##         Position   n
## 1         Center 163
## 2        Center    3
## 3    Point guard 287
## 4    Point Guard   1
## 5  Power forward 306
## 6 Shooting guard 275
## 7  Small forward 254</code></pre>
<p>We find a number of issues:</p>
<p><strong>Round drafted</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>There are two different representations of U (undrafted), because
one of them has a trailing space.</p></li>
<li><p>Our dataset doesnt contain any players that were drafted in
round 9. This is noted but not likely to cause issues because the sample
is quite small, and round 9 didnt exist past 1989. This will be
discussed again later on.</p></li>
<li><p>Very few players are drafted in other high round numbers, such as
round 10 (only 1 player). This may cause problems, because the factor
level 10 can only exist in either the training or testing data, but not
both.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Position</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p>Again, there are two different representations of Center, due to
a trailing space.</p></li>
<li><p>There are two different representations of Point guard, this time
due to a letter case.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>We now fix these issues:</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb13"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb13-1"><a href="#cb13-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># remove any leading or trailing whitespace in character columns</span></span>
<span id="cb13-2"><a href="#cb13-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">data.frame</span>(<span class="fu">lapply</span>(data, <span class="cf">function</span>(x) <span class="cf">if</span>(<span class="fu">class</span>(x)<span class="sc">==</span><span class="st">&quot;character&quot;</span>) <span class="fu">trimws</span>(x) <span class="cf">else</span>(x)), <span class="at">stringsAsFactors=</span>F)</span>
<span id="cb13-3"><a href="#cb13-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb13-4"><a href="#cb13-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># replace &#39;Point Guard&#39; with &#39;Point guard&#39;</span></span>
<span id="cb13-5"><a href="#cb13-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data<span class="sc">$</span>Position[data<span class="sc">$</span>Position <span class="sc">==</span> <span class="st">&quot;Point Guard&quot;</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="st">&quot;Point guard&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb13-6"><a href="#cb13-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb13-7"><a href="#cb13-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># check it worked</span></span>
<span id="cb13-8"><a href="#cb13-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">count</span>(Round_Drafted)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##    Round_Drafted   n
## 1              1 712
## 2             10   1
## 3              2 338
## 4              3  38
## 5              4  24
## 6              5   4
## 7              6   7
## 8              7   5
## 9              8   3
## 10             U 157</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb15"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb15-1"><a href="#cb15-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">count</span>(Position)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##         Position   n
## 1         Center 166
## 2    Point guard 288
## 3  Power forward 306
## 4 Shooting guard 275
## 5  Small forward 254</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="correlations-of-regressors-with-outcome-variable" class="section level2">
<h2>Correlations of regressors with outcome variable</h2>
<p>As a simple way to get a sense of which of the numeric regressors are
correlated with the outcome, we take the correlation coefficient of each
numeric regressor with the outcome variable (TARGET_5Yrs).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb17"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb17-1"><a href="#cb17-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># generate correlation matrix</span></span>
<span id="cb17-2"><a href="#cb17-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlations <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">round</span>(<span class="fu">cor</span>(<span class="fu">as.numeric</span>(data<span class="sc">$</span>TARGET_5Yrs), <span class="fu">Filter</span>(is.numeric, data)),<span class="dv">2</span>)</span>
<span id="cb17-3"><a href="#cb17-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlations[,<span class="fu">order</span>(<span class="fu">abs</span>(correlations),<span class="at">decreasing =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>)] <span class="co"># display, ordered by absolute values</span></span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##         GP        MIN        PTS        FGM        FTM       OREB       DREB 
##       0.42       0.34       0.34       0.34       0.31       0.31       0.31 
##        TOV        FG.        STL        BLK        AST Year_Debut        FT. 
##       0.29       0.25       0.25       0.22       0.19      -0.16       0.10 
##   Win_Perc   X3P.Made       X3P. 
##       0.07       0.04       0.00</code></pre>
<p>Some interesting observations are: * The correlation between the
outcome and respecively win percentage and three pointer metrics appear
to be close to 0. * The correlation between the outcome and the year
debut appears to be negative despite the fact that we would expect it to
be 0.</p>
</div>
<div id="distributions-of-character-variables-by-outcome" class="section level2">
<h2>Distributions of character variables, by outcome</h2>
<p>For the non-numeric variables, we cant use correlation coefficients.
However, we can inspect the relationship between these variables and the
outcome through bar charts.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb19"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb19-1"><a href="#cb19-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># plot for round drafted</span></span>
<span id="cb19-2"><a href="#cb19-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb19-3"><a href="#cb19-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">select</span>(Round_Drafted, TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb19-4"><a href="#cb19-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">group_by</span>(Round_Drafted, TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">tally</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb19-5"><a href="#cb19-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">group_by</span>(TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">proportion =</span> n<span class="sc">/</span><span class="fu">sum</span>(n)) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb19-6"><a href="#cb19-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">ggplot</span>(<span class="fu">aes</span>(<span class="at">x =</span> Round_Drafted, <span class="at">y =</span> proportion, <span class="at">fill =</span> TARGET_5Yrs)) <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="fu">geom_bar</span>(</span>
<span id="cb19-7"><a href="#cb19-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">stat =</span> <span class="st">&quot;identity&quot;</span>, <span class="at">position =</span> <span class="fu">position_dodge</span>()) <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="fu">ylab</span>(</span>
<span id="cb19-8"><a href="#cb19-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>      <span class="st">&quot;proportion of the outcome group&#39;s players drafted in the round&quot;</span>) <span class="co"># + scale_x_discrete(limits = c(seq(1, 10), &quot;U&quot;))</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb20"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb20-1"><a href="#cb20-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># plot for position</span></span>
<span id="cb20-2"><a href="#cb20-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb20-3"><a href="#cb20-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">select</span>(Position, TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb20-4"><a href="#cb20-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">group_by</span>(Position, TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">tally</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb20-5"><a href="#cb20-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">group_by</span>(TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">proportion =</span> n<span class="sc">/</span><span class="fu">sum</span>(n)) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb20-6"><a href="#cb20-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">ggplot</span>(<span class="fu">aes</span>(<span class="at">x =</span> Position, <span class="at">y =</span> proportion, <span class="at">fill =</span> TARGET_5Yrs)) <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="fu">geom_bar</span>(</span>
<span id="cb20-7"><a href="#cb20-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="at">stat =</span> <span class="st">&quot;identity&quot;</span>, <span class="at">position =</span> <span class="fu">position_dodge</span>()) <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="fu">ylab</span>(</span>
<span id="cb20-8"><a href="#cb20-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>      <span class="st">&quot;proportion of the outcome group&#39;s players in the position&quot;</span>) <span class="co">#+ scale_x_discrete(limits = c(&quot;Point guard&quot;, &quot;Shooting guard&quot;, &quot;Center&quot;, &quot;Power forward&quot;, &quot;Small forward&quot;))</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<p><strong>Round drafted</strong></p>
<p>In basketball, we would expect better players to be drafted in an
earlier round (with a lower round number) and the undrafted (U) players
to be worse.</p>
<p>There is a clear difference in the distribution of round numbers for
those who reached 5 years and those who did not. Among those with
TARGET_5Yrs = 1, more than 65% were drafted in the first round, and
fewer than 10% were undrafted.</p>
<p><strong>Position</strong></p>
<p>We see that there is a slight difference in distribution of positions
between those who made 5 years and those who didnt.</p>
<p>We conclude that both round drafted and position are likely to be
relevant.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="iii-pre-processing-dataset" class="section level1">
<h1>III: Pre-processing Dataset</h1>
<p>We now move on to first preparing the data for, and then fitting,
models. Where possible, we will do this using tidymodels methods to make
it easier to fit and compare several models.</p>
<div id="create-indicator-variables" class="section level2">
<h2>Create indicator variables</h2>
<p>Using the step_dummy function from recipes (part of tidymodels), we
create dummy columns for the categorical variables (Round Drafted and
Position). The function replaces each categorical variable by n-1 dummy
columns, where n is the number of categories the variable can take, to
avoid the dummy variable trap.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb21"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb21-1"><a href="#cb21-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># step_dummy doesn&#39;t give the first value of the variable a dummy. </span></span>
<span id="cb21-2"><a href="#cb21-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># For round drafted, it makes sense for this to be undrafted players</span></span>
<span id="cb21-3"><a href="#cb21-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># so we code U as 0 to make it the first value</span></span>
<span id="cb21-4"><a href="#cb21-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data<span class="sc">$</span>Round_Drafted[data<span class="sc">$</span>Round_Drafted <span class="sc">==</span> <span class="st">&quot;U&quot;</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">0</span></span>
<span id="cb21-5"><a href="#cb21-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb21-6"><a href="#cb21-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># define recipe - create dummies for round drafted and position</span></span>
<span id="cb21-7"><a href="#cb21-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>dummy_multi_choice_rec <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">recipe</span>(<span class="sc">~</span> ., <span class="at">data =</span> data) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb21-8"><a href="#cb21-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">step_dummy</span>(Round_Drafted, Position) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb21-9"><a href="#cb21-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">prep</span>()</span>
<span id="cb21-10"><a href="#cb21-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb21-11"><a href="#cb21-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># execute the steps in the recipe</span></span>
<span id="cb21-12"><a href="#cb21-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_to_split <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">bake</span>(dummy_multi_choice_rec, <span class="at">new_data =</span> data) <span class="co">#%&gt;% select(-Name)</span></span>
<span id="cb21-13"><a href="#cb21-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb21-14"><a href="#cb21-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(<span class="fu">head</span>(data_to_split))</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="correct-the-round-drafted-variable" class="section level2">
<h2>Correct the Round Drafted variable</h2>
<p>In 1989 the structure of the draft changed from 10 rounds to just 2.
So, post-1989, fewer players were drafted each year, and rounds drafted
values other than 1, 2 and undrafted ceased to exist.</p>
<p>To correct for this change, we will need to create a time dummy
variable and add interaction terms to the Round_Drafted_# dummy
variables.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb22"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb22-1"><a href="#cb22-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create Dummy variables for debut before 1989</span></span>
<span id="cb22-2"><a href="#cb22-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_to_split<span class="sc">$</span>debut_before_1989 <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">ifelse</span>(data_to_split<span class="sc">$</span>Year_Debut <span class="sc">&gt;=</span> <span class="dv">1989</span>, <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb22-3"><a href="#cb22-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb22-4"><a href="#cb22-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Vector of names for the new interaction columns</span></span>
<span id="cb22-5"><a href="#cb22-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>names <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">paste0</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Round_Drafted_&quot;</span>, <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;1&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;10&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;2&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;3&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;4&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;5&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;6&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;7&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;8&quot;</span>), <span class="st">&quot;_before_1989&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb22-6"><a href="#cb22-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb22-7"><a href="#cb22-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create interaction columns for Round_Drafted_# with Year_debut_before_1989</span></span>
<span id="cb22-8"><a href="#cb22-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_to_split[names] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">lapply</span>(</span>
<span id="cb22-9"><a href="#cb22-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">select</span>(data_to_split,<span class="fu">starts_with</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Round_Drafted&quot;</span>)), <span class="cf">function</span>(x) x<span class="sc">*</span>data_to_split<span class="sc">$</span>debut_before_1989)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>When considering the effect of Round_Drafted:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[\begin{equation}

\beta_1Round\_Drafted\_\# + \beta_2Round\_Drafted\_\# \  *
Year\_Debuted\_Before\_1989 \\

(\beta_1 \ +   \beta_2Year\_Debuted\_Before\_1989 )Round\_Drafted\_\#

\end{equation}\]</span></p>
<p>Where:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[\begin{equation}
Year\_Debuted\_Before\_1989 =
     \begin{cases}
       1 &amp;\quad\text{if Year_Debut}&lt;1989\\
       0 &amp;\quad\text{if Year_Debut} \ge1989 \\
     \end{cases}
\end{equation}\]</span></p>
</div>
<div id="split-dataset-into-training-and-testing" class="section level2">
<h2>Split dataset into training and testing</h2>
<p>Using the initial_split function from rsample (part of tidymodels),
we split the data into training and testing, using (the default) 75% of
observations for training and 25% for testing. The same data and samples
will be used by all models. To preserve the overall class distribution,
we stratify on the outcome variable (TARGET_5Yrs).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb23"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb23-1"><a href="#cb23-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">1423</span>) <span class="co"># fix training-testing split for our project</span></span>
<span id="cb23-2"><a href="#cb23-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_split <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">initial_split</span>(data_to_split, <span class="at">strata =</span> TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb23-3"><a href="#cb23-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb23-4"><a href="#cb23-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_training <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_split <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">training</span>()</span>
<span id="cb23-5"><a href="#cb23-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_testing <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_split <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">testing</span>()</span>
<span id="cb23-6"><a href="#cb23-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb23-7"><a href="#cb23-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">sprintf</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Data had %s obs, now split into training (%s obs) and testing (%s obs)&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb23-8"><a href="#cb23-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="fu">nrow</span>(data), <span class="fu">nrow</span>(data_training), <span class="fu">nrow</span>(data_testing))</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Data had 1289 obs, now split into training (966 obs) and testing (323 obs)&quot;</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb25"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb25-1"><a href="#cb25-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># check proportions of outcome variable values are the same across training and testing</span></span>
<span id="cb25-2"><a href="#cb25-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(data_testing <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">count</span>(TARGET_5Yrs) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">proportion =</span> <span class="fu">round</span>(n<span class="sc">/</span><span class="fu">sum</span>(n),<span class="dv">2</span>)))</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="iv-model-development" class="section level1">
<h1>IV: Model development</h1>
<div id="evaluation-metrics" class="section level2">
<h2>Evaluation metrics</h2>
<p>We begin by thinking about which metrics will be most useful to
calculate for each model.</p>
<p>Our dataset is imbalanced, with 63% of players reaching 5 years, and
37% not reaching 5 years. Because of this, it would be misleading to use
a simple accuracy metric. We will instead focus on
<strong>balanced</strong> accuracy, which is the average of sensitivity
(true positive rate) and specifity (true negative rate), which we will
also inspect. This normalizes true positive and true negative
predictions by the number of positive and negative observations
respectively.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb27"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb27-1"><a href="#cb27-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>evaluation_metrics <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">metric_set</span>(bal_accuracy, spec, sens)</span></code></pre></div>
</div>
<div id="logistic-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Logistic regression</h2>
<div id="a-baseline-logistic-regression-with-all-predictors" class="section level4">
<h4>A baseline: logistic regression with all predictors</h4>
<p>The model development section starts with a logistic regression model
fit on all predictors, using tidymodels. As an introductory stage, the
model will also be used to evaluate significance of our predictor
variables according to the t-test statistics in the summary below.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb28"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb28-1"><a href="#cb28-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>logistic_model <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">logistic_reg</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb28-2"><a href="#cb28-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_engine</span>(<span class="st">&quot;glm&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb28-3"><a href="#cb28-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_mode</span>(<span class="st">&quot;classification&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb28-4"><a href="#cb28-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">fit</span>(TARGET_5Yrs <span class="sc">~</span>., <span class="at">data=</span>data_training)</span>
<span id="cb28-5"><a href="#cb28-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(<span class="fu">tidy</span>(logistic_model) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">arrange</span>(p.value)) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">scroll_box</span>(<span class="at">height =</span> <span class="st">&quot;400px&quot;</span>) <span class="co">#%&gt;% as_tibble() %&gt;% print(n=40)</span></span></code></pre></div>

<p><em>Note</em>: The logistic model includes one dummy variable for all
but one level (the reference level) of each categorical variable.</p>
<p>We can use the p-values or t-test statistics shown in the output to
conclude whether the variable coefficients are significant (ie.
significantly different from 0). At the 5% significance level, the
significant coefficients are those with p-values below 0.05 or with
t-test statistic values above 1.9600. Based on the output of logistic
regression, the significant variables are:</p>
<ul>
<li>GP: games played per season</li>
<li>Win_Perc: the winning percentage of the team the player plays
for</li>
<li>Year_Debut: the year the player debuted his career</li>
<li>(Intercept):</li>
<li>Round_Drafted_X1: Indicator Variable for players drafted in Round
1</li>
<li>FG.: Average field goal success percentage</li>
<li>X3P.Made: Average number of Three-Pointers made per game</li>
<li>OREB: Average number of offensive rebounds per game</li>
</ul>
<p>This is indeed a striking result: one might expect the game
performance of a player to be indicative of his talent and therefore of
his ability to go further in the NBA. Year debut being significant,
there seems to be a time trend in the NBA drafting process whereby
talented players tend to get drafted around the same time. A possible
explanation is that drafting more talented players at the same time
increases competitiveness in the league, pushing talented players to
play even better and stay longer in the NBA. Additionally, college
basketball may have improved over time meaning that prospects in recent
years may be better than before.</p>
<p>However, we should note that all the variables related to points
scored by a player in a game such as the total number of points, free
throws, 3 pointers etc. are all highly correlated. In particular, the
insignificance of free throw metrics may be a result of
multicollinearity and not due the lack of association with the outcome.
Similarly, it may be argued that performance on offense and defense
captured by variables such as steal, block, assist, rebound etc. exhibit
correlation. Top players in the NBA are generally good in both offense
and defense (for example Lebron James).</p>
<p>A final note on significance regarding categorical variables:
Logistic regression uses <em>reference level coding</em>. The t-test
compares each of the non-reference categories to the reference (omitted)
one. It is quite possible for none of those to be significant, but there
to be significant differences amongst the non-reference categories.</p>
<p><strong>Predictions and model accuracy</strong></p>

<span id="cb29-8"><a href="#cb29-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">model =</span> <span class="st">&quot;logistic&quot;</span>)</span>

<div id="implementation-of-gradient-descent" class="section level3">
<h3>Implementation of Gradient Descent</h3>
<p>As a first step towards fitting a logistic regression model, we
implement a gradient descent algorithm to find the model parameters that
minimise the log loss function given by:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
L(\beta) = - \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} [y_{i} \times log(\sigma(x_{i}^T
\beta)) + (1-y_{i})\times log(1-\sigma(x_{i}^T \beta))]
\]</span></p>
<p>where:</p>
<ul>
<li>X is the matrix of predictor variables</li>
<li>y is the vector of the outcome variable</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(\beta\)</span> is the vector of
coefficients in the logistic regression model</li>
<li><span class="math inline">\(\sigma\)</span> is the logistic sigmoid
function given by <span class="math inline">\(\sigma(x_i^T\beta) =
\frac{1}{1+e^-(x_i^T\beta)}\)</span></li>
</ul>
<p>For simplicity we omit the division by <span class="math inline">\(\frac{1}{n}\)</span> as it doesnt affect our
minimisation problem.</p>
<p><strong>Note</strong>: Here we assume an unregularised logistic
regression with 0 penalty term</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb30"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb30-1"><a href="#cb30-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># defining the sigmoid function</span></span>
<span id="cb30-2"><a href="#cb30-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sigmoid <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(x) {</span>
<span id="cb30-3"><a href="#cb30-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="dv">1</span> <span class="sc">/</span> (<span class="dv">1</span> <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="fu">exp</span>(<span class="sc">-</span>x))</span>
<span id="cb30-4"><a href="#cb30-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb30-5"><a href="#cb30-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb30-6"><a href="#cb30-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># implementing the loss function in code</span></span>
<span id="cb30-7"><a href="#cb30-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>logistic_loss <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(X, y, beta) {</span>
<span id="cb30-8"><a href="#cb30-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  X <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">unname</span>(<span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(X)) <span class="co"># remove column names</span></span>
<span id="cb30-9"><a href="#cb30-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  y <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.numeric</span>(<span class="fu">as.character</span>(y)) <span class="co"># converting the factors of the outcome first to strings then to numeric type</span></span>
<span id="cb30-10"><a href="#cb30-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  loss <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">0</span></span>
<span id="cb30-11"><a href="#cb30-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="cf">for</span> (i <span class="cf">in</span> <span class="dv">1</span><span class="sc">:</span><span class="fu">nrow</span>(X)) {</span>
<span id="cb30-12"><a href="#cb30-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    X_i_B <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(X[i, ] <span class="sc">*</span> beta)</span>
<span id="cb30-13"><a href="#cb30-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    p_hat <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sigmoid</span>(X_i_B)</span>
<span id="cb30-14"><a href="#cb30-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    loss <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> loss <span class="sc">+</span> (y[i] <span class="sc">*</span> <span class="fu">log</span>(p_hat) <span class="sc">+</span> (<span class="dv">1</span> <span class="sc">-</span> y[i]) <span class="sc">*</span> <span class="fu">log</span>(<span class="dv">1</span> <span class="sc">-</span> p_hat))</span>
<span id="cb30-15"><a href="#cb30-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  }</span>
<span id="cb30-16"><a href="#cb30-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  loss</span>
<span id="cb30-17"><a href="#cb30-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span></code></pre></div>
<p>The gradient of the log loss function is:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\nabla L(\beta) = X^T(\sigma(X\beta)-Y)
\]</span></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb31"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb31-1"><a href="#cb31-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># implementing the gradient in code</span></span>
<span id="cb31-2"><a href="#cb31-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>gradient <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(X, y, beta) {</span>
<span id="cb31-3"><a href="#cb31-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  X <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">unname</span>(<span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(X))</span>
<span id="cb31-4"><a href="#cb31-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  y <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.numeric</span>(<span class="fu">as.character</span>(y))</span>
<span id="cb31-5"><a href="#cb31-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  beta <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(beta, <span class="fu">length</span>(beta), <span class="dv">1</span>) <span class="co"># converting a beta to a column vector of length length(beta)</span></span>
<span id="cb31-6"><a href="#cb31-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(<span class="fu">t</span>(X) <span class="sc">%*%</span> (<span class="fu">sigmoid</span>(X <span class="sc">%*%</span> beta) <span class="sc">-</span> y), <span class="fu">ncol</span>(X), <span class="dv">1</span>) <span class="co"># returning the gradient vector as a column vector of length ncol(X)</span></span>
<span id="cb31-7"><a href="#cb31-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb31-8"><a href="#cb31-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb31-9"><a href="#cb31-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># the gradient descent algorithm</span></span>
<span id="cb31-10"><a href="#cb31-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient_descent#Description</span></span>
<span id="cb31-11"><a href="#cb31-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>gradient_descent <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(X, y, loss_function) {</span>
<span id="cb31-12"><a href="#cb31-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  X <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">unname</span>(<span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(X))</span>
<span id="cb31-13"><a href="#cb31-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  X <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">scale</span>(X) <span class="co"># standardising the predictors (columns in the X matrix) for greater stability</span></span>
<span id="cb31-14"><a href="#cb31-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  y <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.numeric</span>(<span class="fu">unlist</span>(y))</span>
<span id="cb31-15"><a href="#cb31-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  i <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">0</span></span>
<span id="cb31-16"><a href="#cb31-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  beta_prev <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.matrix</span>(<span class="fu">rep</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="fu">ncol</span>(X)), <span class="fu">ncol</span>(X), <span class="dv">1</span>) <span class="co"># initialise the coefficient vector to be all zero</span></span>
<span id="cb31-17"><a href="#cb31-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  initial_loss_value <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">logistic_loss</span>(X, y, beta_prev)</span>
<span id="cb31-18"><a href="#cb31-18" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  gamma <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fl">0.01</span> <span class="co"># the step</span></span>
<span id="cb31-19"><a href="#cb31-19" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  beta_next <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> beta_prev <span class="sc">-</span> <span class="fu">as.matrix</span>((gamma <span class="sc">*</span> <span class="fu">gradient</span>(X, y, beta_prev)), <span class="fu">ncol</span>(X), <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-20"><a href="#cb31-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="cf">while</span> (<span class="fu">abs</span>(<span class="fu">loss_function</span>(X, y, beta_next) <span class="sc">-</span> <span class="fu">loss_function</span>(X, y, beta_prev)) <span class="sc">&gt;</span> <span class="fl">0.001</span>) {</span>
<span id="cb31-21"><a href="#cb31-21" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    beta_diff <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">gradient</span>(X, y, beta_next) <span class="sc">-</span> <span class="fu">gradient</span>(X, y, beta_prev)</span>
<span id="cb31-22"><a href="#cb31-22" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    gamma_num <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">as.numeric</span>(<span class="fu">t</span>(beta_next <span class="sc">-</span> beta_prev) <span class="sc">%*%</span> beta_diff)</span>
<span id="cb31-23"><a href="#cb31-23" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    gamma_denom <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(beta_diff<span class="sc">^</span><span class="dv">2</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-24"><a href="#cb31-24" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    gamma <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">abs</span>(gamma_num) <span class="sc">/</span> gamma_denom <span class="co"># Update step</span></span>
<span id="cb31-25"><a href="#cb31-25" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    beta_prev <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> beta_next</span>
<span id="cb31-26"><a href="#cb31-26" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    beta_next <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> beta_prev <span class="sc">-</span> <span class="fu">as.matrix</span>((gamma <span class="sc">*</span> <span class="fu">gradient</span>(X, y, beta_prev)), <span class="fu">ncol</span>(X), <span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-27"><a href="#cb31-27" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    i <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> i <span class="sc">+</span> <span class="dv">1</span></span>
<span id="cb31-28"><a href="#cb31-28" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  }</span>
<span id="cb31-29"><a href="#cb31-29" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  final_loss_value <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">logistic_loss</span>(X, y, beta_next)</span>
<span id="cb31-30"><a href="#cb31-30" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">paste0</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Initial loss: &quot;</span>, initial_loss_value))</span>
<span id="cb31-31"><a href="#cb31-31" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">print</span>(<span class="fu">paste0</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Final loss after &quot;</span>, i, <span class="st">&quot; iterations: &quot;</span>, final_loss_value))</span>
<span id="cb31-32"><a href="#cb31-32" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">return</span>(beta_next)</span>
<span id="cb31-33"><a href="#cb31-33" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span></code></pre></div>
<p>We now apply the gradient-descent algorithm to estimate the
coefficients of a logistic regression of our target on a subset of
predictors.</p>
<p>The chosen predictors are likely to be weakly correlated, hence they
avoid a potential multicollinearity problem in our model. The chosen
predictors have p-value below 0.05 and capture the most prominent
factors affecting the performance of a player in the NBA. The predictors
are: games played, winning percentage of the team, year of debut,
drafted in the first round, field goals percentage, three pointers made
and offensive rebound.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb32"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb32-1"><a href="#cb32-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>regressors_grad_desc <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;GP&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Win_Perc&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Year_Debut&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Round_Drafted_X1&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;FG.&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;X3P.Made&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;OREB&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb32-2"><a href="#cb32-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb32-3"><a href="#cb32-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_grad_desc <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_training <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fu">all_of</span>(regressors_grad_desc),TARGET_5Yrs))</span>
<span id="cb32-4"><a href="#cb32-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb32-5"><a href="#cb32-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># scaling the regressors</span></span>
<span id="cb32-6"><a href="#cb32-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="cf">for</span> (var <span class="cf">in</span> regressors_grad_desc){</span>
<span id="cb32-7"><a href="#cb32-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  data_grad_desc[ , var] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">scale</span>(data_grad_desc[ , var])</span>
<span id="cb32-8"><a href="#cb32-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb32-9"><a href="#cb32-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>X_gd <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_grad_desc <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="sc">-</span>TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb32-10"><a href="#cb32-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>y_gd <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_grad_desc <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb32-11"><a href="#cb32-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>coefficients_gd <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">gradient_descent</span>(X_gd, y_gd, logistic_loss)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Initial loss: -669.580176420896&quot;
## [1] &quot;Final loss after 10 iterations: -540.385589899183&quot;</code></pre>
<p>To evaluate the efficiency of our algorithm, we compare the estimated
coefficients from the gradient descent algorithm to those from the
direct implementation of the logistic regression (using the glm
library)</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb34"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb34-1"><a href="#cb34-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>logistic_fit <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">glm</span>(<span class="fu">unlist</span>(y_gd) <span class="sc">~</span> GP <span class="sc">+</span> Win_Perc <span class="sc">+</span> Year_Debut <span class="sc">+</span> Round_Drafted_X1 <span class="sc">+</span> FG. <span class="sc">+</span> X3P.Made <span class="sc">+</span> OREB <span class="sc">-</span> <span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="at">data=</span>data_grad_desc, <span class="at">family=</span><span class="st">&quot;binomial&quot;</span>) <span class="co">#we omit the intercept</span></span>
<span id="cb34-2"><a href="#cb34-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb34-3"><a href="#cb34-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># display logistic fit and gradient descent coefficients side-by-side</span></span>
<span id="cb34-4"><a href="#cb34-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(<span class="fu">list</span>(logistic_fit<span class="sc">$</span>coefficients, <span class="fu">as.double</span>(coefficients_gd)))</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="lasso-knn" class="section level2">
<h2>LASSO + KNN</h2>
<p><!-- - Relatively interpretable  -->
<!-- - High Dimensionality  --></p>
<p>With 40 different regressors, before we fit a KNN model, we want to
complete some process of subset selection to not only draw some
inference about which variables may be more significant, but also reduce
the dimensionality of the KNN model as KNN is susceptible to the curse
of dimensionality. For this, we use LASSO.</p>
<p>Below we are going to estimate the Lasso Regression model using the
GLMNET function. This entails setting alpha = 1. It should be noted that
by changing the family parameter to binomial, the GLMNET function
fits a traditional logistic regression model for the log-odds
according to the documentation. For Lambda, we are using a sequence from
-6 to 0 in increments of 0.5.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb35"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb35-1"><a href="#cb35-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_training_lasso <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_training <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="sc">-</span>TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb35-2"><a href="#cb35-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_testing_lasso <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_testing <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="sc">-</span>TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb35-3"><a href="#cb35-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb35-4"><a href="#cb35-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>outcome_training <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_training <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb35-5"><a href="#cb35-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>outcome_testing <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_testing <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(TARGET_5Yrs)</span>
<span id="cb35-6"><a href="#cb35-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb35-7"><a href="#cb35-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Estimate the Lasso Regression Model</span></span>
<span id="cb35-8"><a href="#cb35-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>model_lasso <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">glmnet</span>(<span class="fu">data.matrix</span>(data_training_lasso), <span class="at">y =</span> <span class="fu">data.matrix</span>(outcome_training), <span class="at">intercept =</span> <span class="cn">FALSE</span>, <span class="at">alpha =</span> <span class="dv">1</span> , <span class="at">lambda =</span> <span class="dv">10</span><span class="sc">^</span><span class="fu">seq</span>(<span class="at">from =</span> <span class="sc">-</span><span class="dv">6</span>, <span class="at">to =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="at">by =</span> <span class="fl">0.5</span>), <span class="at">family =</span> <span class="st">&quot;binomial&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb35-9"><a href="#cb35-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(model_lasso, <span class="at">xvar =</span> <span class="st">&quot;lambda&quot;</span>) <span class="co">#Plot the Lasso Regression Model against Log Lambda Values</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb36"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb36-1"><a href="#cb36-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># #Return the coefficients of the Lasso Regression Model for the different values of Lambda</span></span>
<span id="cb36-2"><a href="#cb36-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>beta_hat <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">coef</span>(model_lasso)</span>
<span id="cb36-3"><a href="#cb36-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb36-4"><a href="#cb36-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Optimal value of Lambda: estimates the value for Lambda that gives the largest area beneath the ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) Curve. These areas are estimated using K-fold cross-validation.</span></span>
<span id="cb36-5"><a href="#cb36-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>cv_lasso <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">cv.glmnet</span>(<span class="at">x =</span> <span class="fu">data.matrix</span>(data_training_lasso), <span class="at">y =</span> <span class="fu">data.matrix</span>(outcome_training), <span class="at">type.measure =</span> <span class="st">&quot;mse&quot;</span> , <span class="at">nfolds =</span> <span class="dv">10</span>)</span>
<span id="cb36-6"><a href="#cb36-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lambda <span class="ot">=</span> cv_lasso<span class="sc">$</span>lambda.min</span>
<span id="cb36-7"><a href="#cb36-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Return the coefficients associated with the model that produces the largest area under the ROC curve in the training data.</span></span>
<span id="cb36-8"><a href="#cb36-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>beta_hat2 <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">coef</span>(model_lasso, <span class="at">s =</span> lambda)</span>
<span id="cb36-9"><a href="#cb36-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(cv_lasso)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="768" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb37"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb37-1"><a href="#cb37-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>beta_hat2[<span class="fu">which</span>(<span class="fu">rowSums</span>(beta_hat2) <span class="sc">&gt;</span> <span class="dv">0</span>),] <span class="co"># print non-zero coefficients</span></span></code></pre></div>

<div id="analysis-of-the-lasso-model-above" class="section level3">
<h3>Analysis of the Lasso model above</h3>
<p><strong>Significant predictors</strong></p>
<p>Printing the coefficient estimates for a range of Lambdas was
insightful as it was interesting to see what variables persist as the
penalty increases.</p>
<p>Most Notably:</p>
<p>-GP (Number of Games Played in Debut Season)</p>
<p>-MIN (Average Number of Minutes played per game)</p>
<p>-PTS (Average Number of Points per game)</p>
<p>-FG. (Field Goal Percentage)</p>
<p>-FTM (Free Throws Made)</p>
<p>-FT. (Free Throws Percentage)</p>
<p>-OREB (Average Offensive Rebounds per game)</p>
<p>-AST (Average Assists per game)</p>
<p>-BLK (Average Blocks per game)</p>
<p>-Win_Perc (Win Percentage of Team in Debut Season)</p>
<p>-Round_Drafted_1 (Dummy variable for players drafted in Round 1)</p>
<p>-Position_Point.guard (Point Guard position)</p>
<p>-Round_Drafted_1_before_1989 (Interaction variable for players
drafted in Round 1 before 1989)</p>
<p>One could develop a convincing story to justify the coefficients
displayed above:</p>
<p>Teams that win more games with a particular group will be more likely
to keep most of those players, especially the main contributors.
Therefore, we should not be surprised that the coefficients for Win
Percentage and Number of Games Played are positive and relatively
large.</p>
<p>What perhaps is more interesting is the observation that defensive
rebounds, steals and turnovers seem to have a relatively insignificant
impact on a players ability to reach year 5. Whilst there are players
who pride themselves on their ability to defend (E.g. Draymond Green -
4x NBA All-Defensive First Team), in reality the structure of the game
seems to lend itself more to offensive attributes and point scoring
ability.</p>
<p>It is important to note that we cannot consider this regression
causal. Our investigation does not revolve around some treatment
variable that we could conclude is randomly assigned. Additionally,
there are still confounding variables that are not accounted for in our
dataset.</p>
<p>For example, we have no information on the injury status of players.
Players may have played through injuries or been injured in their final
college season, thus influencing what round they get drafted in.</p>
<p>Several players like Blake Griffin, Joel Embiid, Ben Simmons and
Julius Randle suffered season ending injuries in their rookie seasons.
Despite this, all of these plays have gone on to become NBA stars and
play beyond 5 years.</p>
<p>Our current specification fails to accurately capture circumstances
where confounding variables like injury and health, team chemistry,
coaching, and off-the-field status can impact the likelihood of a player
reaching year 5.</p>
<p>The data suggests a positive association between being drafted in the
first round and the likelihood of making it to year 5. This is
consistent with the notion that players drafted in the first round will
have performed better in college or international leagues before
declaring for the draft.</p>
<p>One could argue that the round a player is drafted in functions as a
proxy for what teams expect their ability to be. It must be noted that
some teams may not certain draft players for schematic or logistical
reasons; Some teams may need to improve a particular position and not
draft the best available player.</p>
<p>However, one could therefore argue that teams may be more lenient
with first round draft picks and give them more opportunities than lower
drafted players; Teams believe that first round draft picks have a
higher ceiling and may just need time to adapt to the NBA.</p>
<p>Using the results from the Lasso Regression, we want to choose the
following subset of regressors to train our KNN model: GP, MIN, PTS
,FG., FTM, FT., OREB, AST, BLK, Win_Perc, Round_Drafted,
Position_Point.guard, Round_Drafted_1_before_1989</p>
<p>Logistic regression suggests: GP, Win_Perc, Year_Debut,
Round_Drafted_X1, FG., X3P.Made, OREB</p>
<p>LASSO suggests: GP, MIN, PTS, FG., FTM, FT., OREB, AST, BLK,
Win_Perc, Round_Drafted_X1, Position_Point.guard,
Round_Drafted_1_before_1989</p>
<p>What is notably absent from the lasso results compared to the
logistic regression is the time effect of being drafted. Whilst lasso
suggests that shooting from the field, offensive rebounds, assists and
blocks are the best way for players to make an impact. In general,
scoring more points and spending time on field is likely to improve the
likelihood of retention.</p>
<p>As KNN models are susceptible to the curse of dimensionality, it is
important to choose the smallest number of variables possible whilst
trying to maximise the amount of information gained.</p>
<p>Looking at the Lasso results above, this subset of regressors appears
to represent the variables that capture the most information.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb39"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb39-1"><a href="#cb39-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>vars_lasso_output <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;GP&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;MIN&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;PTS&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;FG.&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;FTM&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;FT.&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;OREB&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;AST&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;BLK&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Win_Perc&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Round_Drafted_X1&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Position_Point.guard&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Round_Drafted_1_before_1989&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb39-2"><a href="#cb39-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb39-3"><a href="#cb39-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_training_lasso_output <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_training <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fu">all_of</span>(vars_lasso_output),TARGET_5Yrs))</span>
<span id="cb39-4"><a href="#cb39-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_testing_lasso_output <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> data_testing <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span> <span class="fu">select</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="fu">all_of</span>(vars_lasso_output),TARGET_5Yrs))</span>
<span id="cb39-5"><a href="#cb39-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb39-6"><a href="#cb39-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># use sqrt(training obs count) for k, as widely suggested</span></span>
<span id="cb39-7"><a href="#cb39-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>knn <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">nearest_neighbor</span>(<span class="at">mode =</span> <span class="st">&quot;classification&quot;</span>, <span class="at">engine =</span> <span class="st">&quot;kknn&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb39-8"><a href="#cb39-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                        <span class="at">neighbors =</span> <span class="fu">round</span>(<span class="fu">sqrt</span>(<span class="fu">nrow</span>(data_training_lasso_output)))) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb39-9"><a href="#cb39-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">fit</span>(TARGET_5Yrs <span class="sc">~</span>., <span class="at">data =</span> data_training_lasso_output)</span>
<span id="cb39-10"><a href="#cb39-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb39-11"><a href="#cb39-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># predictions</span></span>
<span id="cb39-12"><a href="#cb39-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>predictions_knn <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> knn <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb39-13"><a href="#cb39-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">predict</span>(data_testing_lasso_output) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb39-14"><a href="#cb39-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">bind_cols</span>(data_testing_lasso_output)</span>
<span id="cb39-15"><a href="#cb39-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb39-16"><a href="#cb39-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#predictions$TARGET_5Yrs &lt;- as.factor(predictions$TARGET_5Yrs)</span></span>
<span id="cb39-17"><a href="#cb39-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#kable(metrics(predictions, truth=TARGET_5Yrs, estimate = .pred_class))</span></span>
<span id="cb39-18"><a href="#cb39-18" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb39-19"><a href="#cb39-19" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># evaluation</span></span>
<span id="cb39-20"><a href="#cb39-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>metrics_knn <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">evaluation_metrics</span>(predictions_knn, <span class="at">truth=</span>TARGET_5Yrs, <span class="at">estimate =</span> .pred_class) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb39-21"><a href="#cb39-21" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">model =</span> <span class="st">&quot;knn&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb39-22"><a href="#cb39-22" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(metrics_knn)</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="svm" class="section level2">
<h2>SVM</h2>
<p>As a next step, we check for non-linearity using another
classification approach - that of Support Vector Machines (SVM). SVM
allows us to classify data points according to non-linear decision
boundaries.</p>
<div id="svm-with-a-radial-kernel" class="section level3">
<h3>SVM with a radial kernel</h3>
<p>When using a Radial Basis (RBF) Kernel, the SVM algorithm measures
the Euclidian distance (as a measure of similarity) between points in
the space. Consequently, it has a very local behaviour in the sense that
only nearby training observations affect the classification of a test
observation. Similar to the KNN model, RBF Kernel has the advantage of
overcoming space complexity as, instead of reusing all of the dataset,
it only needs to store the support vectors during training. The support
vectors are the data points that are the closest to the decision
boundary and define the margin of the classifier.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb40"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb40-1"><a href="#cb40-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>svm_rbf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">svm_rbf</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-2"><a href="#cb40-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_engine</span>(<span class="st">&quot;kernlab&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-3"><a href="#cb40-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_mode</span>(<span class="st">&quot;classification&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-4"><a href="#cb40-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">fit</span>(TARGET_5Yrs <span class="sc">~</span> ., <span class="at">data =</span> data_training)</span>
<span id="cb40-5"><a href="#cb40-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#svm_rbf</span></span>
<span id="cb40-6"><a href="#cb40-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb40-7"><a href="#cb40-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># predictions</span></span>
<span id="cb40-8"><a href="#cb40-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>predictions_svm_rbf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> svm_rbf <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-9"><a href="#cb40-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">predict</span>(data_testing) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-10"><a href="#cb40-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">bind_cols</span>(data_testing)</span>
<span id="cb40-11"><a href="#cb40-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  </span>
<span id="cb40-12"><a href="#cb40-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># evaluation</span></span>
<span id="cb40-13"><a href="#cb40-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>metrics_svm_rbf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">evaluation_metrics</span>(predictions_svm_rbf, <span class="at">truth=</span>TARGET_5Yrs, <span class="at">estimate =</span> .pred_class) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb40-14"><a href="#cb40-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">model =</span> <span class="st">&quot;svm_rbf&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb40-15"><a href="#cb40-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(metrics_svm_rbf)</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="decision-tree" class="section level2">
<h2>Decision Tree</h2>
<div id="an-interpretable-non-baseline-model" class="section level3">
<h3>An interpretable non-baseline model</h3>
<p>We now move onto a very different classification approach:
decision-tree classification. Decision trees have the advantage of being
very interpretable, allowing us to directly visualise the relationship
between the outcome and the explanatory variables.</p>
<p>As decision trees are very susceptible to the curse of
dimensionality, we will not use the full set of regressors, and use the
subset identified as significant by the earlier LASSO method.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb44"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb44-1"><a href="#cb44-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>tree <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">decision_tree</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb44-2"><a href="#cb44-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_engine</span>(<span class="st">&quot;rpart&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb44-3"><a href="#cb44-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">set_mode</span>(<span class="st">&quot;classification&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb44-4"><a href="#cb44-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">fit</span>(TARGET_5Yrs <span class="sc">~</span> ., <span class="at">data =</span> data_training_lasso_output)</span>
<span id="cb44-5"><a href="#cb44-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb44-6"><a href="#cb44-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>tree <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb44-7"><a href="#cb44-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">extract_fit_engine</span>() <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb44-8"><a href="#cb44-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">rpart.plot</span>(<span class="at">roundint =</span> <span class="cn">FALSE</span>, <span class="at">type =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

<span id="cb45-3"><a href="#cb45-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">predict</span>(data_testing_lasso_output) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
