<p><strong>Interpretation of results</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Games played appears to be the most important factor determining the
success of an NBA player. Players who play more games in a season tend
to be better integrated and may play a more impactful role in the
strategy of the team. Playing more games in a season will allow players
to get more experience and gain confidence not just in themselves but
also from the coaches and fans.</li>
<li>Round_Drafted_X1 is a second important factor. This is consistence
with the results above. We could argue that first round draft picks have
a high ceiling and are generally more talented.</li>
<li>Free throws made and percentage are both important as they reflect
the players ability to handle stressful situations and their
understanding of the rules and how to draw fouls.</li>
<li>Win percentage is another important factor as stronger teams are
less likely to trade players away as doing so could risk hurting
chemistry or schematic advantages.</li>
<li>This tree-like visualisation is very useful in that it allows one
with very little background understanding to generate predictions
regarding the classification of an NBA player, by moving through the
tree from top to bottom.
<ul>
<li>Every node consists of 3 numbers: the top one denotes the predicted
class (0 or 1), the middle one denotes the probability of belonging to
class 1, and last one denotes the percentage of the observations used in
that node.</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Observations</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The tree classifier yields a balanced accuracy of 72.7%.</li>
<li>The relatively lower predictive accuracy is compensated by the
simplicity and the interpretability of the decision tree model. Since
there are several other factors affecting a players success in the NBA,
some of which we cant control for in our models (such as genetic
attributes, injury, nationality etc.), it is not surprising that our
decision tree does not achieve an exceptionally high predictive
accuracy. For what it is, the model seems to be performing reasonably
well.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="random-forests" class="section level2">
<h2>Random Forests</h2>
<div id="high-dimensional-with-a-focus-on-predictive-accuracy" class="section level4">
<h4>High-dimensional, with a focus on predictive accuracy</h4>
<p>To improve upon the performance of the decision tree classifier, we
consider a random forest model. Random forests use decision trees as
building blocks to construct more powerful predictive models.</p>
<p>Decision trees have low bias (they make no assumption about the
functional form of the true relationship between the outcome and the
predictors) but suffer from high variance (in that the structure of the
decision tree is highly sensitive to changes in individual points of the
data, so the model certainly overfits). Random forests attempt to
address that issue by lowering variance at the expense of a small
increase in bias.</p>
<p>Random forest is built by fitting multiple decision trees, then
taking the average of the resulting predictions. Each time a split is
considered, a random sample of m predictors is chosen as split
candidates from the full set of predictors. This ensures that the
resulting predictions of the decision trees are not highly correlated
(averaging over highly correlated values does not lead to substantial
reduction in variance).</p>
<p>As random forests can deal with high-dimensional data, we will use
all regressors (excluding those identified as collinear or
irrelevant).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb46"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb46-1"><a href="#cb46-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">set.seed</span>(<span class="dv">1423</span>) <span class="co"># set seed to fix outcome of random forest</span></span>
<span id="cb46-2"><a href="#cb46-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb46-3"><a href="#cb46-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#random forests fit with tidymodels</span></span>
<span id="cb46-4"><a href="#cb46-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>rf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">rand_forest</span>(<span class="at">trees =</span> <span class="dv">100</span>, <span class="at">mode=</span><span class="st">&quot;classification&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb46-5"><a href="#cb46-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="fu">set_engine</span>(<span class="st">&quot;randomForest&quot;</span>) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb46-6"><a href="#cb46-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="fu">fit</span>(TARGET_5Yrs<span class="sc">~</span>., <span class="at">data =</span> data_training)</span>
<span id="cb46-7"><a href="#cb46-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#rf</span></span>
<span id="cb46-8"><a href="#cb46-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># predictions</span></span>
<span id="cb46-9"><a href="#cb46-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>predictions_rf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> rf <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb46-10"><a href="#cb46-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">predict</span>(data_testing) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>

<span id="cb46-15"><a href="#cb46-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#predictions_rf$TARGET_5Yrs &lt;- as.factor(predictions_rf$TARGET_5Yrs)</span></span>
<span id="cb46-16"><a href="#cb46-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#truth refers to the actual results and estimate refers to what the model predicted</span></span>
<span id="cb46-17"><a href="#cb46-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#kable(metrics(predictions_rf, truth=TARGET_5Yrs, estimate = .pred_class))</span></span>

<span id="cb46-20"><a href="#cb46-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>metrics_rf <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">evaluation_metrics</span>(predictions_rf, <span class="at">truth=</span>TARGET_5Yrs, <span class="at">estimate =</span> .pred_class) <span class="sc">%&gt;%</span></span>
<span id="cb46-21"><a href="#cb46-21" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  <span class="fu">mutate</span>(<span class="at">model =</span> <span class="st">&quot;random_forest&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb46-22"><a href="#cb46-22" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">kable</span>(metrics_rf)</span></code></pre></div>
